08725nam a22009735i 9780824893835DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20222023hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248938357 a10.1515/97808248938352doi  a(DE-B1597)618914  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aDS556.8b.B86 2022 7aHIS0480002bisacsh04a959.7/03223/eng/2022081700aBuilding a Republican Nation in Vietnam, 1920–1963 /ced. by Nu-Anh Tran, Tuong Vu. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2022] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b3 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tINTRODUCTION Rethinking Vietnamese Republicanism -- tCHAPTER ONE A Republican Moment in the Study of Modern Vietnam -- tCHAPTER TWO Early Republicans’ Concept of the Nation: Trần Trọng Kim and Việt Nam sử lược -- tCHAPTER THREE The Self-Reliant Literary Group and Colonial Republicanism in the 1930s -- tCHAPTER FOUR Trần Văn Tùng’s Vision of a New Nationalism for a New Vietnam -- tCHAPTER FIVE How Democratic Should Vietnam Be? The Constitutional Transition of 1955–1956 and the Debate on Democracy -- tCHAPTER SIX Personalism, Liberal Capitalism, and the Strategic Hamlet Campaign -- tCHAPTER SEVEN “They Eat the Flesh of Children” Migration, Resettlement, and Sectionalism in South Vietnam, 1954–1957 -- tCHAPTER EIGHT Creating the National Library in Saigon Colonial Legacies, Republican Visions, and Reading Publics, 1946–1958 -- tCHAPTER NINE Striving for the Quintessence Building a New Identity of National Literature Based on Creative Freedom -- tCHAPTER TEN When State Propaganda Becomes Social Knowledge -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWestern observers have long considered communism to be synonymous with Vietnam’s modern historical experience. Eager to make sense of the North Vietnamese victory in the Vietnam War, scholars and journalists have spilled much ink on the history of Vietnamese communists. But this preoccupation has obscured the diversity of ideas and experiences that defined Vietnam in the twentieth century, in which communism represented just one of many tendencies. Building a Republican Nation in Postcolonial Vietnam, 1920–1963, posits that republicanism shaped modern Vietnam no less profoundly than communism. Republicans championed representative government, the universal rights of man, civil liberties, and the primacy of the nation. These ideas infused the thinking of Vietnamese reformers, dissidents, and revolutionaries from the 1900s onward, including many men and women who went on to lead the struggle for independence. Republicanism was also one of the chief inspirations for the establishment of the Republic of Vietnam (also known as South Vietnam) in 1955.This interdisciplinary volume brings together eleven essays by historians, political scientists, literary scholars, and sociologists, who make use of fresh sources to study the development of republicanism from the colonial period to the First Republic of Vietnam (1955–1963). The introduction by coeditors Nu-Anh Tran and Tuong Vu critically analyzes the existing scholarship on the First Republic, explains how the concept of republicanism can illuminate developments in the Saigon-based state, and situates the regime in a comparative context with South Korea. Peter Zinoman’s chapter reviews the historiography on republicanism and modern Vietnam and heralds the arrival of the “republican moment” in the field of Vietnam studies. Several chapters by Nguyễn Lương Hải Khôi, Martina Thucnhi Nguyen, and Yen Vu examine the transformation of republican ideas. Nu-Anh Tran and Duy Lap Nguyen explore competing concepts of democracy and the factional politics of the First Republic. The essays by Jason Picard, Cindy Nguyen, Hoàng Phong Tuấn, Nguyễn Thị Minh, and Y Thien Nguyen analyze nation- and state-building efforts in the 1950s and 1960s. Collectively, the essays give voice to Vietnamese republicans, from the ideas they espoused to the institutions they built and the legacies they left behind.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aRepublicanismzVietnam (Republic)vCongresses. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh1 aHoàng, Phong Tuan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHải Khôi, Nguyễn Lương, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLap Nguyen, Duy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNguyen, Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNguyen, Duy Lap, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNguyen, Martina Thucnhi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNguyen, Y Thien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNguyễn, Lương Hải Khôi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNguyễn, Thị Minh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhong Tuấn, Hoàng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPicard, Jason A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThucnhi Nguyen, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThị Minh, Nguyễn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTran, Nu-Anh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTran, Nu-Anh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVu, Tuong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb